t, England":"Ditcheat, Somerset, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1200–about 1237":"circa 1200–circa 1237","1200–1237":"1200–1237","–Female":"Overleden","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1038–Male":"1038–Overleden","1175–Male":"1175–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1295":"1295","1180":"1180","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1237":"1237","1038":"1038","1224":"1224","about 1237":"circa 1237","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","1342":"1342","about 1200":"circa 1200","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Ierland","Ditcheat, Somerset, England":"Ditcheat, Somerset, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1200–about 1237":"about 1200–about 1237","1200–1237":"1200–1237","–Female":"Deceased","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1038–Male":"1038–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1295":"1295","1180":"1180","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1237":"1237","1038":"1038","1224":"1224","about 1237":"about 1237","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","1342":"1342","about 1200":"about 1200","Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland":"Buttevant, County Cork, Ireland","Ditcheat, Somerset, England":"Ditcheat, Somerset, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mede","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Bartolo, Croce, Dante, Domenico, Giorgio, Luigi, Pietro, Salvatore, Vincenzo, Vito.  French/Haitian Guerline, Jean Marie.","Italian: from the female personal name <i>Fede</i>, from Latin <i>fides</i> ‘faith’.","Italian: from a short form of the personal name   Federico  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Federico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenic, Antonio, Guerino, Armando, Salvatore, Domenico, Gino, Mario, Nino, Sal, Carmine, Guido, Alfredo, Angelo, Benito, Carmela.  Spanish Jose, Ruben, Carlos, Jesus, Rosario, Enrique, Francisco, Juan.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Federico</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Friedrich  ). Compare   Federick   and   Frederico  ."]},{"name":"Di Fede","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): patronymic or metronymic from the male or female personal name   Fede  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Mede was born about 1200, in Ditcheat, Somerset, England, his father, Francois de Mede, was 27 and his mother, Gladys ferch Rhiwallon, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Gwenllian verch Gruffyd. He died about 1237, in England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1200–about 1237":"umbes 1200–umbes 1237","1200–1237":"1200–1237","–Female":"Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1038–Male":"1038–Surnud"